Price, however, accused the school where she has worked for eight years of violating her academic freedom. She also said that she is being punished for challenging the male-dominated power structure at Appalachian State.

'I think all this happened because I threatened those that are truly in power at Appalachian State,' Price told the Watauga Democrat.

The Chronicle of Higher Education 
reports that Price has hired a lawyer and filed a sex-discrimination 
complaint against ASU through the Equal Employment Opportunity 
Commission.

